          "body": "Verses 13-26 form the chapter's longest and most detailed section, and they are often skipped in devotional reading. The narrator devotes thirteen verses to the mechanics of Joseph's famine administration: money, then livestock, then land and bodies, then the institution of a permanent 20% agricultural tax. The progression is remorseless and precise. First, all the silver of Egypt and Canaan flows to Pharaoh's house (v. 14). When the silver is gone, livestock follows — horses, flocks, herds, donkeys (v. 17). When the livestock is gone, the Egyptians offer their land and their persons: 'Buy us and our land for food, and we and our land will be slaves to Pharaoh' (v. 19). Joseph consolidates all private Egyptian land for Pharaoh (v. 20) and relocates the population to the cities (v. 21) — only the priestly class retains its land through Pharaoh's standing grant (vv. 22, 26). The new order is then announced: you are Pharaoh's; here is seed; at harvest return a fifth to Pharaoh (vv. 23-24). The Egyptians receive this as deliverance — 'You have saved our lives!' (v. 25) — not as oppression. Joseph's management is just in its context: he feeds rather than abandons the population, provides seed for the future, and sets a tax that leaves 80% of the harvest in the farmer's hands. Ancient Near Eastern parallels show 20-33% as standard royal taxation. The narrative endorses Joseph's administration without moralizing about it. Yet the careful reader cannot miss the irony: the same institution — Pharaoh's ownership of land and people — will become the mechanism of Israel's oppression in Exodus 1. Joseph builds the machine that will later grind his descendants."
