          "title": "Jacob's dying request — faith that refuses Egypt as home",
          "body": "The chapter's final movement (vv. 27-31) begins with Jacob's prosperity and ends with his deathbed oath-demand. Having lived seventeen years in Egypt — longer than Joseph's time in slavery before his elevation — Jacob summons his son for a covenant transaction. The ritual described in v. 29, 'place your hand under my thigh,' is the same gesture Abraham required of his servant in Genesis 24:2, 9. It is an oath sworn by the life-giving power of the body, invoking the covenant promises tied to physical descendants. Jacob's request invokes chesed and emet — 'kindness and faithfulness' — the technical vocabulary of covenant loyalty (cf. Gen. 24:27; 2 Sam. 2:6; Ps. 25:10; Ex. 34:6 in God's self-declaration). He is not asking for a family favor; he is invoking covenant obligation. The content of the request is stark: 'do not bury me in Egypt' (v. 29). After seventeen years of prosperity in the best of Egypt's land, Jacob refuses to let Egypt be his final address. His burial must be at Machpelah — the cave Abraham purchased from Ephron the Hittite as the first owned real estate in Canaan (Gen. 23:17-20; 49:29-32). That cave is a down payment on the promise. To be buried there is to cast a vote for the covenant — to say with the body what the mouth has confessed: God will give this land to my descendants. Hebrews 11:21 cites this exact scene as an act of faith: 'By faith Jacob, as he was dying, blessed each of the sons of Joseph, and worshiped, leaning on the top of his staff.' The worship that closes the chapter (v. 31) is not resignation; it is triumph. Jacob has secured the oath; Joseph has sworn; and the dying patriarch bows in adoration of the God who will keep both His own promises and Joseph's."
