          "title": "The chapter's canonical horizon — sojourn, exodus, and the promised land",
          "body": "Genesis 47 cannot be read in isolation from Genesis 15:13-16, where God told Abraham: 'Your descendants will be sojourners in a land that is not theirs, and will serve them, and they will be afflicted for four hundred years; but I will also judge the nation whom they will serve, and afterward they will come out with many possessions.' Every element of that prediction is now either in motion or visible on the horizon. The sojourn is happening — Jacob names his life magur (sojourning, v. 9). The servitude is anticipated by the Egyptians' voluntary self-enslavement to Pharaoh in vv. 19-21, the same structure that will become Israel's burden in Exodus 1:8-14. The 'coming out' is anticipated by Jacob's refusal to be buried in Egypt — his bones insist on Canaan before the Exodus happens. Joseph's own bones will make the same confession: Exodus 13:19 records that Moses carried Joseph's bones out of Egypt, honoring the oath of Genesis 50:25. The chapter is therefore not merely administrative history; it is prophetic narrative. The narrator places the reader in the exact moment when the covenant family is most comfortable, most prosperous, most settled — and makes the dying patriarch insist that none of it is home. The pattern is one the New Testament reads as characteristic of faith itself: Abraham and the patriarchs 'confessed that they were strangers and exiles on the earth... they desire a better country, that is, a heavenly one' (Heb. 11:13-16). Jacob's hand-under-thigh oath is the most physical, most embodied expression of that confession in the entire patriarchal narrative."
