        "excerpt": "Joseph settled his father and his brothers and gave them a possession in the land of Egypt, in the best of the land... Joseph provided his father and his brothers and all his father's household with food, according to their little ones.",
        "body": "Verses 11-12 form a brief but crucial paragraph before the narrator pivots to the famine's macro-economic effects. Joseph does two things: he gives the family a possession (*achuzzah*) and he provides them food calibrated to their need (*le-phi ha-taph* — 'according to their little ones,' lit. 'to the mouth of the small ones'). The word *achuzzah* (possession, v. 11) appears earlier in Genesis 17:8, where God promises Abraham 'all the land of Canaan for an everlasting possession.' Its use here is deliberately ironic: the covenant family's first *achuzzah* is in Egypt, not Canaan. It is a genuine possession — real land, real livestock, real security — but it is the wrong possession in the wrong land. The narrator's placement of this verse immediately before the famine-administration narrative (vv. 13-26) creates a precise contrast: Israel's possession is given freely by Joseph; Egypt's possessions will be systematically purchased by Joseph for Pharaoh.\n\nThe detail 'according to their little ones' is pastoral and personal. Joseph is not distributing rations by household size or economic contribution; he is feeding people according to the vulnerable. The same man who managed a national grain-distribution system at scale never lost the face of the smallest member of his father's house. Swindoll (Joseph: A Man of Integrity and Forgiveness, 1998) observes that administrative competence and personal tenderness coexist in Joseph with unusual rarity — he is simultaneously the most powerful man in Egypt outside Pharaoh and the brother who weeps on his brothers' necks (Gen. 45:14-15; 46:29).\n\nThe canonical significance of Joseph's provision for Israel during the famine points forward to the Passover and the Exodus. In both cases, the same night that brings death to Egypt brings deliverance to Israel. The pattern is embedded here in miniature: 'there was no food in all the land' (v. 13) — except for Israel, who ate by Joseph's hand. The one whose brothers sold him into Egypt has become the means of their preservation. Genesis 45:5 and 8 name this explicitly as God's purpose, and chapter 47 is its working out in the details of daily provision."
